<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-graphing-inequalities-in-two-unknowns" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Graphing Inequalities in Two Unknowns</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.3 Linear Inequalities
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Represent linear inequalities in two unknowns graphically
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        <m>20</m> minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To guide learners in visualizing how a single linear boundary splits a two-dimensional coordinate plane into two halves, and discovering how to isolate the correct solution half-plane using a test point.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        Demonstrate how to sketch the boundary line (solid versus dashed), prompt learners to choose strategic test points like <m>(0,0)</m> to evaluate the inequality, and oversee the clean shading of the satisfying region.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>3</m> or <m>4</m> learners
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Materials needed:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Graph paper (one sheet per group)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Colored pencils or markers (at least two different colors)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A ruler
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                In your groups:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            On your graph paper, draw a coordinate system with <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> axes, with values from <m>-5</m> to <m>5</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using one color, draw the line <m>y = x + 1</m> on your coordinate system.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Test a point not on the line, such as <m>(0, 0)</m>, in the inequality <m>y \gt x + 1</m>. Does the point satisfy the inequality? If yes, mark it with your first color.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Shade the region where <m>y \gt x + 1</m> is true using your first color.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            On a new piece of graph paper, draw another coordinate system and repeat steps 2-4 for the inequality <m>2x + y \le 4</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss with your group: How is graphing an inequality in two unknowns similar to graphing an inequality in one unknown? How is it different?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your graphs and observations with the class.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
            <p>
                For an inequality like <m>y \gt x + 1</m>, first draw the boundary line <m>y = x + 1</m> using a dashed line (since it's a strict inequality). Then test a point like <m>(0, 0)</m>: if <m>0 \gt 0 + 1</m> is false, shade the region that doesn't contain <m>(0, 0)</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                For an inequality like <m>2x + y \le 4</m>, draw the boundary line <m>2x + y = 4</m> using a solid line (since it includes equality). Then test a point like <m>(0, 0)</m>: if <m>2(0) + 0 \le 4</m> is true, shade the region that contains <m>(0, 0)</m>.
            </p>
        </hint>
    </activity>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

