    <insight>
        <p>
            Graphing an inequality in two unknowns means representing every point <m>(x, y)</m> that satisfies the inequality on a coordinate plane.
        </p>
        <p>
            To graph an inequality like <m>y \gt x + 1</m>:
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        First, draw the <term>boundary line</term> by graphing the related equation <m>y = x + 1</m>.
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Use a <term>dashed line</term> for strict inequalities (<m>\gt</m> or <m>\lt</m>) because points on the line don't satisfy the inequality.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Use a <term>solid line</term> for inclusive inequalities (<m>\ge</m> or <m>\le</m>) because points on the line do satisfy the inequality.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Test a point</term> not on the boundary line, such as the origin <m>(0, 0)</m>, to determine which side of the line contains the solution set.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Shade</term> the region that contains all points satisfying the inequality.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            The shaded region represents the solution set—all ordered pairs <m>(x, y)</m> that make the inequality true. Understanding and graphing these regions is essential for solving systems of inequalities and for optimization problems in real-world applications.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Graph the inequality <m>y \lt -x + 2</m> on a coordinate plane.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            First, we draw the boundary line <m>y = -x + 2</m>. This line passes through <m>(0, 2)</m> and <m>(2, 0)</m>, with a slope of <m>-1</m>.
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Since we have a strict inequality (<m>\lt</m>), we use a <term>dashed line</term> to show that points on the line are not included in the solution set.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            To determine which side to shade, we test the point <m>(0, 0)</m>: Is <m>0 \lt -0 + 2</m>? Yes, <m>0 \lt 2</m> is true. So <m>(0, 0)</m> is in the solution set.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We shade the region <term>below</term> the line (the region that contains <m>(0, 0)</m>).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <image xml:id="img-inequality-y-le-negative-x-plus-2" width="70%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Draw grid with visible boxes
                            \draw[gray!40, thin] (-2,-2) grid (5,4);
                            
                            % Draw axes with arrows for continuity
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-2,0) -- (5,0) node[right, above] {$x$};
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-2) -- (0,4) node[left, above] {$y$};
                            
                            % Shade the region below the line (where y &lt; -x + 2)
                            \fill[fill=blue!30, opacity=0.6] (-2,-2) -- (4,-2) -- (-2,4) -- cycle;
                            
                            % Draw boundary line y = -x + 2 as dashed, extended to edges
                            \draw[dashed, thick, black] (-2,4) -- (4,-2);
                            
                            % Draw tick marks and labels (except at origin)
                            \foreach \x in {-1, 1, 2, 3, 4} {
                                \draw (\x, -0.2) -- (\x, 0.2);
                                \node[below=3pt] at (\x, 0) {$\x$};
                            }
                            \foreach \y in {-1, 1, 2, 3} {
                                \draw (-0.2, \y) -- (0.2, \y);
                                \node[left=3pt] at (0, \y) {$\y$};
                            }
                            
                            % Draw only one 0 at the intersection in the lower left quarter
                            \node[below left=5pt] at (0, 0) {$0$};
                            
                            % Label the line equation on the line itself
                            \node at (2, 0.5) [fill=white, inner sep=2pt, font=\small] {$y = -x + 2$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve and graph the inequality <m>2x + y \le 4</m> on a coordinate plane.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            First, we rewrite as an equation: <m>2x + y = 4</m>, or <m>y = -2x + 4</m>. This line has a <m>y</m>-intercept of <m>4</m> and a slope of <m>-2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since we have an inclusive inequality (<m>\le</m>), we use a <term>solid line</term> to show that points on the line are included in the solution set.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            To determine which side to shade, we test the point <m>(0, 0)</m>: Is <m>2(0) + 0 \le 4</m>? Yes, this is true. So <m>(0, 0)</m> is in the solution set.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We shade the region <term>below</term> the line (the region that contains <m>(0, 0)</m>).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <image xml:id="img-inequality-2x-plus-y-le-4" width="70%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Draw grid with visible boxes
                            \draw[gray!40, thin] (-1,-1) grid (5,5);
                            
                            % Draw axes with arrows for continuity
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-1,0) -- (5,0) node[right, above] {$x$};
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,5) node[left, above] {$y$};
                            
                            % Shade the region below the line (including the line since it's ≤)
                            \fill[fill=green!30, opacity=0.6] (-1,-1) -- (2.5,-1) -- (-0.5,5) -- (-1,5) -- cycle;
                            
                            % Draw boundary line 2x + y = 4 (y = -2x + 4) as solid
                            \draw[solid, thick, black] (-0.5,5) -- (2.5,-1);
                            
                            % Draw tick marks and labels (except at origin)
                            \foreach \x in {-1, 1, 2, 3, 4} {
                                \draw (\x, -0.2) -- (\x, 0.2);
                                \node[below=3pt] at (\x, 0) {$\x$};
                            }
                            \foreach \y in {1, 2, 3, 4} {
                                \draw (-0.2, \y) -- (0.2, \y);
                                \node[left=3pt] at (0, \y) {$\y$};
                            }
                            
                            % Draw only one 0 at the intersection
                            \node[below left=5pt] at (0, 0) {$0$};
                            
                            % Label the line equation on the line itself
                            \node at (0.5, 3) [fill=white, inner sep=2pt, font=\small] {$y = -2x + 4$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Determine the solution region for <m>y \gt \frac{1}{2}x - 1</m> and represent it graphically.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            First, we draw the boundary line <m>y = \frac{1}{2}x - 1</m>. This line has a <m>y</m>-intercept of <m>-1</m> and a slope of <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since we have a strict inequality (<m>\gt</m>), we use a <term>dashed line</term> to show that points on the line are not included in the solution set.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            To determine which side to shade, we test the point <m>(0, 0)</m>: Is <m>0 \gt \frac{1}{2}(0) - 1</m>? Yes, <m>0 \gt -1</m> is true. So <m>(0, 0)</m> is in the solution set.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We shade the region <term>above</term> the line (the region that contains <m>(0, 0)</m>).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <image xml:id="img-inequality-x-minus-2y-lt-2" width="70%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Draw grid with visible boxes
                            \draw[gray!40, thin] (-1,-1) grid (5,5);
                            
                            % Draw axes with arrows for continuity
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-1,0) -- (5,0) node[right, above] {$x$};
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,5) node[left, above] {$y$};
                            
                            % Shade the region above the line
                            \fill[fill=red!30, opacity=0.6] (-1,5) -- (5,5) -- (5,1.5) -- (0,-1) -- (-1,-1) -- cycle;
                            
                            % Draw boundary line y = 0.5x - 1 as dashed, within grid area
                            \draw[dashed, thick, black] (0,-1) -- (5,1.5);
                            
                            % Draw tick marks and labels (except at origin)
                            \foreach \x in {-1, 1, 2, 3, 4} {
                                \draw (\x, -0.2) -- (\x, 0.2);
                                \node[below=3pt] at (\x, 0) {$\x$};
                            }
                            \foreach \y in {1, 2, 3, 4} {
                                \draw (-0.2, \y) -- (0.2, \y);
                                \node[left=3pt] at (0, \y) {$\y$};
                            }
                            
                            % Draw only one 0 at the intersection
                            \node[below left=5pt] at (0, 0) {$0$};
                            
                            % Label the line equation on the line itself
                            \node at (2.5, 0.25) [fill=white, inner sep=2pt, font=\small] {$y = \frac{1}{2}x - 1$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Graph the inequality <m>y \ge 2x - 3</m> on a coordinate plane. Clearly label the axes, boundary line, and shaded region.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The boundary line is <m>y = 2x - 3</m>, which has a <m>y</m>-intercept of <m>-3</m> and a slope of <m>2</m>. Since this is an inclusive inequality (<m>\ge</m>), we use a solid line.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Testing <m>(0, 0)</m>: Is <m>0 \ge 2(0) - 3</m>? Yes, <m>0 \ge -3</m> is true.
                </p>
                <p>
                    We shade the region above and on the boundary line.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <image width="70%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                % Draw grid with visible boxes
                                \draw[gray!40, thin] (-1,-4) grid (4,4);
                                
                                % Draw axes with arrows
                                \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-1,0) -- (4,0) node[right, above] {$x$};
                                \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-4) -- (0,4) node[left, above] {$y$};
                                
                                % Shade the region above the line
                                \fill[fill=blue!30, opacity=0.6] (-1,-4) -- (-0.5,-4) -- (3.5,4) -- (4,4) -- (4,-4) -- cycle;
                                
                                % Draw boundary line y = 2x - 3 as solid
                                \draw[solid, thick, black] (-0.5, -4) -- (3.5, 4);
                                
                                % Draw tick marks and labels (except at origin)
                                \foreach \x in {-1, 1, 2, 3} {
                                    \draw (\x, -0.2) -- (\x, 0.2);
                                    \node[below=3pt] at (\x, 0) {$\x$};
                                }
                                \foreach \y in {-3, -2, -1, 1, 2, 3} {
                                    \draw (-0.2, \y) -- (0.2, \y);
                                    \node[left=3pt] at (0, \y) {$\y$};
                                }
                                
                                % Draw only one 0 at the intersection
                                \node[below left=5pt] at (0, 0) {$0$};
                                
                                % Label the line
                                \node at (1.5, 1) [fill=white, inner sep=2pt, font=\small] {$y = 2x - 3$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve the inequality <m>x + 2y \gt 6</m> for <m>y</m>, then graph the solution region on a coordinate plane.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    First, we solve for <m>y</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x + 2y &amp; \gt 6</mrow>
                        <mrow>2y &amp; \gt -x + 6</mrow>
                        <mrow>y &amp; \gt -\frac{1}{2}x + 3</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The boundary line is <m>y = -\frac{1}{2}x + 3</m> with a <m>y</m>-intercept of <m>3</m> and slope of <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m>. Since it's a strict inequality (<m>\gt</m>), we use a dashed line.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Testing <m>(0, 0)</m>: Is <m>0 \gt -\frac{1}{2}(0) + 3</m>? No, <m>0 \gt 3</m> is false. So we shade the region that does not contain <m>(0, 0)</m>, which is above the line.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <image width="70%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                % Draw grid with visible boxes
                                \draw[gray!40, thin] (-1,-1) grid (7,5);
                                
                                % Draw axes with arrows
                                \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-1,0) -- (7,0) node[right, above] {$x$};
                                \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,5) node[left, above] {$y$};
                                
                                % Shade the region above the line
                                \fill[fill=green!30, opacity=0.6] (-1,3.5) -- (-1,5) -- (7,5) -- (7,-0.5) -- cycle;
                                
                                % Draw boundary line as dashed
                                \draw[dashed, thick, black] (-1, 3.5) -- (7, -0.5);
                                
                                % Draw tick marks and labels (except at origin)
                                \foreach \x in {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6} {
                                    \draw (\x, -0.2) -- (\x, 0.2);
                                    \node[below=3pt] at (\x, 0) {$\x$};
                                }
                                \foreach \y in {1, 2, 3, 4} {
                                    \draw (-0.2, \y) -- (0.2, \y);
                                    \node[left=3pt] at (0, \y) {$\y$};
                                }
                                
                                % Draw only one 0 at the intersection
                                \node[below left=5pt] at (0, 0) {$0$};
                                
                                % Label the line
                                \node at (4, 1.5) [fill=white, inner sep=2pt, font=\small] {$y = -\frac{1}{2}x + 3$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </p>
            </solution>             
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>   
                <p>
                    Solve and graph: <m>3x - y \le 3</m>
                </p>
            </statement>   
            <solution>
                <p>
                    First, we rewrite as <m>y = 3x - 3</m>. The <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>-3</m> and the slope is <m>3</m>. Since this is an inclusive inequality (<m>\le</m>), we use a solid line.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Testing <m>(0, 0)</m>: Is <m>3(0) - 0 \le 3</m>? Yes, <m>0 \le 3</m> is true.
                </p>
                <p>
                    We shade the region below and on the boundary line (the region that contains <m>(0, 0)</m>).
                </p>
                <p>
                    <image width="70%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                % Draw grid with visible boxes
                                \draw[gray!40, thin] (-3,-5) grid (5,4);
                                
                                % Draw axes with arrows
                                \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-3,0) -- (5,0) node[right, above] {$x$};
                                \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,4) node[left, above] {$y$};
                                
                                % Shade the region below the line
                                \fill[fill=red!30, opacity=0.6] (-1,-5) -- (-0.667,-5) -- (2.333,4) -- (3,4) -- (3,-5) -- cycle;
                                
                                % Draw boundary line y = 3x - 3 as solid
                                \draw[solid, thick, black] (-0.667, -5) -- (2.333, 4);
                                
                                % Draw tick marks and labels (except at origin)
                                \foreach \x in {-2, -1, 1, 2, 3} {
                                    \draw (\x, -0.2) -- (\x, 0.2);
                                    \node[below=3pt] at (\x, 0) {$\x$};
                                }
                                \foreach \y in {-4, -3, -2, -1, 1, 2, 3} {
                                    \draw (-0.2, \y) -- (0.2, \y);
                                    \node[left=3pt] at (0, \y) {$\y$};
                                }
                                
                                % Draw only one 0 at the intersection
                                \node[below left=5pt] at (0, 0) {$0$};
                                
                                % Label the line
                                \node at (1.5, 2) [fill=white, inner sep=2pt, font=\small] {$y = 3x - 3$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <em>Mama Njeri</em> runs a successful catering business in <em>Parkie</em> Nairobi. For an upcoming school fundraiser in Westlands, she needs to prepare <term>ugali</term> and <term>sukuma wiki</term> (collard greens). Let <m>x</m> represent the number of kilograms of ugali and <m>y</m> represent the number of kilograms of sukuma wiki she prepares.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The fundraising committee has the following requirements:
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The total amount of food prepared must not exceed <m>100</m> kg (due to storage space).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                She must prepare at least <m>20</m> kg of ugali (this is the main dish that most learners prefer).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                She must prepare at least <m>15</m> kg of sukuma wiki (to ensure balanced nutrition).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write the inequality representing the total food prepared.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Determine the feasible region by graphing the 3 inequalities representing this situation.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Identify three possible combinations of ugali and sukuma wiki that satisfy all constraints.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If Mama Njeri prepares <m>40</m> kg of ugali and <m>50</m> kg of sukuma wiki, does this combination satisfy all the requirements? Justify your answer using the inequalities.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The inequality representing the total food constraint is:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>x + y \le 100</md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The feasible region is bounded by three constraints:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><m>x + y \le 100</m> (boundary line passes through (0,100) and (100,0))</li>
                                    <li><m>x \ge 20</m> (vertical line at x = 20)</li>
                                    <li><m>y \ge 15</m> (horizontal line at y = 15)</li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The feasible region is a polygon with vertices that can be found by solving the systems of equations formed by the boundaries. Key vertices include:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><m>(20, 15)</m> - intersection of <m>x = 20</m> and <m>y = 15</m></li>
                                    <li><m>(20, 80)</m> - intersection of <m>x = 20</m> and <m>x + y = 100</m></li>
                                    <li><m>(85, 15)</m> - intersection of <m>y = 15</m> and <m>x + y = 100</m></li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <image>
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.06, every node/.style={transform shape=false}]
                                            % 1. Draw a crisp background grid (steps of 10)
                                            \draw[gray!15, thin, step=10] (0,0) grid (110, 110);
                                            
                                            % 2. Draw axes with arrows
                                            \draw[black, thick, -&gt;] (-10,0) -- (115,0) node[right] {$x$ (kg of ugali)};
                                            \draw[black, thick, -&gt;] (0,-10) -- (0,115) node[above] {$y$ (kg of sukuma wiki)};
                                            
                                            % 3. Axis Numbering / Scaling (Steps of 20)
                                            \foreach \x in {20, 40, 60, 80, 100} {
                                                \draw (\x, 2) -- (\x, -2) node[below, font=\tiny] {\x};
                                            }
                                            \foreach \y in {20, 40, 60, 80, 100} {
                                                \draw (2, \y) -- (-2, \y) node[left, font=\tiny] {\y};
                                            }
                                            \node at (-3,-4) [font=\tiny] {0};

                                            % 4. Shade feasible region (Yellow Fill)
                                            \fill[fill=yellow!40, opacity=0.6] (20,15) -- (20,80) -- (85,15) -- cycle;
                                            
                                            % 5. Draw exact boundary lines (extended slightly past intercepts for a realistic look)
                                            \draw[solid, thick, black] (-5,105) -- (105,-5); % x + y = 100
                                            \draw[solid, thick, black] (20, -5) -- (20, 105); % x = 20
                                            \draw[solid, thick, black] (-5, 15) -- (105, 15); % y = 15
                                            
                                            % 6. Mark vertices with distinct scaled dots
                                            \fill[black] (20, 15) circle (30pt);
                                            \fill[black] (20, 80) circle (30pt);
                                            \fill[black] (85, 15) circle (30pt);
                                            
                                            % 7. Label lines precisely (slanted/aligned along the actual line placement)
                                            \node at (50, 60) [above right, font=\small, rotate=-45] {$x + y = 100$};
                                            \node at (20, 50) [left, font=\small] {$x = 20$};
                                            \node at (50, 5) [above, font=\small] {$y = 15$};
                                            
                                            % 8. Label coordinates clean of the lines
                                            \node at (20, 15) [below left, font=\small] {(20, 15)};
                                            \node at (20, 80) [above right, font=\small] {(20, 80)};
                                            \node at (85, 15) [above right, font=\small] {(85, 15)};
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Any point within or on the boundary of the feasible region satisfies all constraints. Three possible combinations are:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><m>(30, 50)</m>: 30 kg of ugali and 50 kg of sukuma wiki</li>
                                    <li><m>(40, 40)</m>: 40 kg of ugali and 40 kg of sukuma wiki</li>
                                    <li><m>(50, 30)</m>: 50 kg of ugali and 30 kg of sukuma wiki</li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                (Students can verify: all satisfy <m>x \ge 20</m>, <m>y \ge 15</m>, and <m>x + y \le 100</m>)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Testing the combination <m>(40, 50)</m>:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Is <m>40 \ge 20</m>? Yes ✓</li>
                                    <li>Is <m>50 \ge 15</m>? Yes ✓</li>
                                    <li>Is <m>40 + 50 \le 100</m>? Is <m>90 \le 100</m>? Yes ✓</li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <strong>Conclusion:</strong> The combination of <m>40</m> kg of ugali and <m>50</m> kg of sukuma wiki satisfies all requirements. Mama Njeri can proceed with this preparation plan.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

